The annotation you might be looking for is the `@JsonManagedReference` and `@JsonBackReference` annotations. 

Circular dependencies can occur when there is a bidirectional relationship between two entities in Hibernate. By default, Jackson (the JSON library used by Hibernate) will attempt to serialize both sides of the relationship, resulting in an infinite loop. 

You can break this circular dependency by using the `@JsonManagedReference` and `@JsonBackReference` annotations from the Jackson library. 

Here's an example of how you can use these annotations:

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    @JsonManagedReference
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class EntityB {
    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "entity_a_id")
    @JsonBackReference
    private EntityA entityA;

    // other properties and methods
}
```

In this example, `EntityA` has a one-to-many relationship with `EntityB`. The `@JsonManagedReference` annotation is placed on the "many" side of the relationship (`EntityA`), and the `@JsonBackReference` annotation is placed on the "one" side of the relationship (`EntityB`). 

With these annotations in place, when serializing `EntityA` to JSON, Jackson will include the associated `EntityB` objects. However, when serializing `EntityB`, the `EntityA` reference will be ignored, hence breaking the circular dependency.

Please note that these annotations are part of the Jackson library, not Hibernate specifically. However, they are commonly used in combination with Hibernate to handle circular dependencies during JSON serialization.

I apologize for the confusion. If you are looking for a solution within Hibernate or the standard Java library, there is no direct annotation to handle circular dependencies. Circular dependencies are typically resolved by using lazy fetching or by breaking the bidirectional relationship.

1. Lazy fetching: By default, Hibernate uses lazy fetching, which means that it will not load the related entities until they are explicitly accessed. This can help to avoid circular dependency issues. However, you should be cautious when using lazy fetching to ensure that proper session management is in place to prevent potential lazy loading exceptions.

Example using lazy fetching:

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class EntityB {
    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @JoinColumn(name = "entity_a_id")
    private EntityA entityA;

    // other properties and methods
}
```

2. Breaking the bidirectional relationship: Another approach is to break the bidirectional relationship by choosing one side to be the owning side and removing the reference from the other side.

Example breaking the bidirectional relationship:

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class EntityB {
    // Remove the entityA reference or make it transient (not persisted)
    // Other properties and methods
}
```

By removing the reference to `EntityA` in `EntityB`, you effectively break the circular dependency.

These solutions are based on Hibernate and the standard Java library without relying on any specific annotations.

Apologies for any confusion caused. Removing the reference to the entity from one side will prevent the circular dependency from being explicitly present in the entity classes. However, it may not completely resolve the circular dependencies issue, especially when it comes to serializing the entities to JSON.

If you remove the reference to `EntityA` from `EntityB`, you may encounter issues while serializing the entities to JSON, as the bi-directional association won't be properly represented. The default behavior of Jackson (the JSON library used by Hibernate) is to recursively serialize the entire object graph, which can result in an infinite loop when there are circular references.

To address this during JSON serialization without using external libraries, you can make use of Jackson's `@JsonIgnore` annotation to selectively exclude the reference to `EntityA` in `EntityB`. However, this approach will omit the reference entirely, which may not be desirable depending on your use case.

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class EntityB {
    // Removing the entityA reference or making it transient (not persisted)
    // Other properties and methods

    @JsonIgnore
    public EntityA getEntityA() {
        return null; // Return null or omit the method
    }
}
```

By providing a `getEntityA()` method annotated with `@JsonIgnore` in `EntityB`, you instruct Jackson to exclude the reference to `EntityA` while serializing `EntityB` to JSON. However, this approach won't preserve the relationship in the JSON representation.

If preserving the relationship is crucial, you may need to consider using third-party libraries like Jackson or Gson, which provide more advanced annotation options like `@JsonManagedReference` and `@JsonBackReference` (as mentioned in the previous response) to handle circular dependencies during JSON serialization with more precision.

Apologies for the confusion earlier. To handle circular dependencies in Hibernate without relying on external libraries, you can make use of `@Transient` annotation on one side of the bidirectional relationship.

Here's an example:

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class EntityB {
    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "entity_a_id")
    @Transient
    private EntityA entityA;

    // other properties and methods
}
```

By adding `@Transient` to the `entityA` field in `EntityB`, you are instructing Hibernate to ignore this property during database mapping. It allows you to break the circular dependency without affecting the database schema.

Please note that using `@Transient` will exclude the `entityA` field from the database mapping, so you won't be able to fetch or persist this relationship using Hibernate. However, it will help in avoiding circular dependency issues during entity mapping and serialization.

Once you mark the field as `@Transient`, you should no longer encounter the `could not determine recommended Jdbc type` error.

The field marked with the `@Transient` annotation will not be persisted in the database. It means that the value of that field will not be stored in the corresponding table column.

In the example provided, marking the `entityA` field in `EntityB` with `@Transient`:

```java
@Entity
public class EntityB {
    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "entity_a_id")
    @Transient
    private EntityA entityA;

    // other properties and methods
}
```

The `entityA` field will not be persisted in the database when `EntityB` instances are saved or updated. The column for this field will not be created in the corresponding database table, and Hibernate will not attempt to perform any database operations for this field.

It's important to note that using `@Transient` only affects the persistence of the field; it does not impact other aspects such as object-relational mapping or in-memory operations.

Yes, the circular dependency issue can potentially be caused by cascading all operations between entities. When bidirectional relationships exist between entities and you have cascading enabled for all operations (`CascadeType.ALL`), it can lead to circular referencing and potentially infinite recursion.

For example, consider the following entities:

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class EntityB {
    @ManyToOne
    private EntityA entityA;

    // other properties and methods
}
```

In this scenario, when you try to persist an instance of `EntityA` that contains a list of `EntityB`, and you have cascading enabled for all operations, Hibernate attempts to cascade the operations to the associated `EntityB` instances. Since `EntityB` has a reference back to `EntityA` through the `entityA` field, it triggers a cascade on `EntityA` again, leading to an infinite loop of cascading operations.

To resolve this circular dependency caused by cascading, you can consider using specific cascade types instead of `CascadeType.ALL` and selectively define the cascade types that are appropriate for your scenario. For example, you can specify only `CascadeType.PERSIST` and `CascadeType.MERGE` if those are the required operations while excluding `CascadeType.ALL`.

```java
@Entity
public class EntityA {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "entityA", cascade = { CascadeType.PERSIST, CascadeType.MERGE })
    private List<EntityB> entityBs;

    // other properties and methods
}
```

By selectively defining the appropriate cascade types, you can avoid the circular dependency issue triggered by cascading all operations.

