To address the circular dependency when serializing to JSON, you can use a combination of `@JsonIgnore` and `@JsonManagedReference` / `@JsonBackReference` annotations from the Jackson library.

Assuming `Basket` has a list of `Kiwi` objects and `Kiwi` has a reference back to `Basket`, you can modify the entity definitions as follows:

```java
@Entity
public class Basket {
    // Other properties and methods

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "basket", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    @JsonManagedReference
    private List<Kiwi> kiwis;

    // Other properties and methods
}

@Entity
public class Kiwi {
    // Other properties and methods

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "basket_id")
    @JsonBackReference
    private Basket basket;

    // Other properties and methods
}
```

In this code snippet, `@JsonManagedReference` is used on the `kiwis` collection in `Basket`, and `@JsonBackReference` is used on the `basket` field in `Kiwi`. This configuration tells Jackson to handle the circular reference by ignoring the `basket` field during the serialization process.

With this setup, the circular dependency between `Basket` and `Kiwi` should be resolved during JSON serialization, which should prevent the infinite loop and the `StackOverflowError`.

Remember to have the Jackson library (e.g., `jackson-core` and `jackson-databind`) present in your project dependencies for these annotations to work.

